1
00:00:03,500 --> 00:00:06,960
We start our exploration of any data set with

2
00:00:06,960 --> 00:00:11,315
univariate visualizations or visualizations of single variables.

3
00:00:11,315 --> 00:00:13,675
By looking at one variable at a time,

4
00:00:13,675 --> 00:00:17,075
we can build an intuition for how each variable is distributed

5
00:00:17,075 --> 00:00:21,515
before moving on to more complicated interactions between variables.

6
00:00:21,515 --> 00:00:24,325
When you start looking at any data set,

7
00:00:24,325 --> 00:00:27,660
keep in mind the goals of your investigation and explore

8
00:00:27,660 --> 00:00:31,495
the variables that will be key to answering your research questions.

9
00:00:31,495 --> 00:00:36,500
If we observe any oddities in the data such as outliers, or missing values,

10
00:00:36,500 --> 00:00:38,400
this can point us to areas where we need to do

11
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:41,905
more cleaning or otherwise perform further inspection.

12
00:00:41,905 --> 00:00:44,600
It often makes sense to integrate this part of

13
00:00:44,600 --> 00:00:48,710
the exploration process into parts of the data wrangling process.

14
00:00:48,710 --> 00:00:52,150
This lesson will focus on two different plot types,

15
00:00:52,150 --> 00:00:57,040
bar charts for qualitative variables and histograms for quantitative variables.

16
00:00:57,040 --> 00:01:01,985
While both of these plot types take the appearance of rectangles on a pair of axes,

17
00:01:01,985 --> 00:01:05,430
you will see how datatype makes these plots distinct.

18
00:01:05,430 --> 00:01:08,650
You will also learn how to use code to create these plots

19
00:01:08,650 --> 00:01:12,870
as well as how to use these plots to gain an understanding of your data.

